<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->  
<solution>
<p>This is one strategy. Other (perhaps faster!...) strategies are possible.</p>
<p>There are three ways to choose at least one blue ball: (first blue, second blue), (first blue, second red), (first red, second blue). Each of these has the following probability of occuring:</p>
<p><alert>(blue, blue)</alert>: At first, there are <m>$d</m> balls to choose from, and <m>$a</m> possible blue balls. So, the first pick has probability <m>P = <math name="aOverD">$a/$d</math></m>. For the second pick, there are now only <math simplify>$d - 1</math> balls left to choose from, and there are <math simplify>$a - 1</math> blue balls remaining. So, to pick blue again has probability <m>P = <math name="secondChoice" simplify>($a - 1)/($d - 1)</math></m>. Combining these two selections gives a total probability for this selection of <m>P = ($aOverD)($secondChoice) = <math name="p1" simplify>($aOverD)($secondChoice)</math></m></p>

<p><alert>(blue, red)</alert>: The first choice again has probability <m>$aOverD</m>. Next, there are <m>$b</m> red balls of the <math simplify>$d - 1</math> balls remaining, so the second choice has probability <math name="secondChoice2" simplify>$b/($d - 1)</math>. Combining these two selections gives a total probability for this selection of <m>P = ($aOverD)($secondChoice2) = <math name="p2" simplify>($aOverD)($secondChoice2)</math></m></p>

<p><alert>(red, blue)</alert>: The first choice has probability <math name="bOverD">$b/$d</math>. Next, there are <m>$a</m> blue balls of the <math simplify>$d - 1</math> balls remaining, so the second choice has probability <math name="secondChoice3" simplify>$a/($d - 1)</math>. Combining these two selections gives a total probability for this selection of <m>P = ($bOverD)($secondChoice3) = <math name="p3" simplify>($bOverD)($secondChoice3)</math></m></p>

<p>The sum of all of these three possiblities gives the total probability of at least one blue ball being selected.</p>
  
  
<p><m>P(\text{at least one blue}) = $p1 + $p2 + $p3 = $sol</m></p>

<p><em>Can you think of another way to do this involving only one probability computation?</em></p>
</solution>
</problem>
